          <section id="sic">
            <h3>Simulation of Irradiation Effects on Silicon Carbide</h3>(Jan'14 - present)
	    <div class="row">	
	    <div class="span7">
	    <h5>Guide:</h5><p>Prof. Narasimhan Swaminathan, Dept. of Mechanical Engineering, IIT Madras</p>
            <h5>Abstract</h5>
            <p>Objective is to run molecular dynamic simulations to determine the effects of nuclear radiation on silicon carbide structures	. Concentrated vacancies in the lattice were simulated and the effect on the tensile strength studied. Concentrated interstitials and anti-sites shall also be introduced in the future. The simulations were run using LAMMPS MD simulator, along with OVITO, for lattice visualisation, and Scilab, for post-processing the results.</p></div>

<div class="span4"><img src="Plane_of_Failure_2_cropped.png" class="img-rounded">
<center><p>Plane of failure for a pure SiC crystal under uni-axial tension </p></center>
 </div>
	</div>
          </section>
	<hr class="separator" />        
	  <section id="ge">
            <h3>Performance Analysis of Inlet Plenum</h3>
            <h5>Guide</h5><p>Mr. R Vidyasagar, Aero-Thermal team, General Electric (Oil & Gas), Bangalore (May'14 - Jul'14)<br>
            <h5>Abstract</h5>
            <p>
              Performed CFD analysis for the inlet plenum of a centrifugal compressor using ICEM CFD and CFX. Also set up a procedure to perform a Design of Experiments (DoE) analysis in Ansys Workbench<copyright />, relating the performance of the plenum to its design specifications, thereby avoiding unnecessary computationally intensive CFD runs.
            </p>
          </section>
          <hr class="separator" />
          <section id="step">
            <h3>Pneumatic Step-Climbing Robot</h3>
            <h5>Guide</h5>
            <p>Dr. Mahesh V Panchagnula, Centre For Innovation, IIT Madras (Jun'12 - Jul'12)</p>
            <br>
            <h5>Abstract</h5>
Objective is to design and develop a pneumatically actuated step-climbing robot. Developed a manually operated robot capable of scaling steps of upto 20 cm height. Also developed a fast, autonomous robot capable of scaling a single step. Additionally, 3 pneumatically actuated clamping mechanisms for round and flat geometries were also designed and implemented. <br><br>
<!--          <center><img src="img/r.gif"> <br></center>
          <center><br><em>The MPC Navigation Algorithm at work</em><br></center> -->
          </section>
          <hr class="separator" />
          <section id="tpi">
            <h3>Quality Enhancement in Sheet Metal Slitting</h3>
                <h5>Guide</h5>
                <p>Mr. Krishna Srinivasan, Corporate Technology Centre, Tube Investments India (Jun'13 - Jul'14)</p>
                <h5>Abstract</h5>
                <p>
                Reviewed literature on methods to improve the end quality of the slitting process of sheet metal. Selected the Roll-slitting process as the rolls obtained are burr-free. Also studied the steel-tube manufacturing processes -- Cold Drawn Welding and Electric Resistance Welding -- used in Tube Products of India.
		</p>
          </section>
